"Leite N.K., Krusche A.V., Ballester M.V.R., Victoria R.L., Richey J.E., Gomes B.M.","Intra and interannual variability in the Madeira River water chemistry and sediment load",2011,"Biogeochemistry","105","1",,"37","51",,,10.1007/s10533-010-9568-5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80052263956&partnerID=40&md5=01d5a55984901b0f2189b0cf7412ad07","CENA, University of São Paulo, Av Centenario, 303-Sao Dimas, Box 96, Piracicaba, SP 13416-903, Brazil; University of Washington, School of Oceanography, Box 355351, Seattle, WA 98195-5351, United States; UNIR, Estrada do Itapirema, Ji-Paraná, RO 78960-000, Brazil","Leite, N.K., CENA, University of São Paulo, Av Centenario, 303-Sao Dimas, Box 96, Piracicaba, SP 13416-903, Brazil; Krusche, A.V., CENA, University of São Paulo, Av Centenario, 303-Sao Dimas, Box 96, Piracicaba, SP 13416-903, Brazil; Ballester, M.V.R., CENA, University of São Paulo, Av Centenario, 303-Sao Dimas, Box 96, Piracicaba, SP 13416-903, Brazil; Victoria, R.L., CENA, University of São Paulo, Av Centenario, 303-Sao Dimas, Box 96, Piracicaba, SP 13416-903, Brazil; Richey, J.E., University of Washington, School of Oceanography, Box 355351, Seattle, WA 98195-5351, United States; Gomes, B.M., UNIR, Estrada do Itapirema, Ji-Paraná, RO 78960-000, Brazil","Concentrations of cations (Na+, Ca2+, Mg2+, K+, NH4+), anions (HCO3-, Cl-, NO3-, SO42-, PO43-) and suspended sediments in the Madeira River water were determined near the city of Porto Velho (RO), in order to assess variation in water chemistry from 2004 to 2007. Calcium and bicarbonate were the dominant cation and anion, respectively. Significant seasonal differences were found, with highest concentrations occurring during the dry season, as expected from the drainage of Andean carbonate-rich substratum. Interannual variations were also observed, but became significant only when annual average discharge was 25% less than normal. Under this atypical discharge condition, bicarbonate was replaced by sulfate, and higher suspended sediment concentrations and loads were also observed. Compared to previously published studies, it appears that no significant changes in water chemistry have occurred during the last 20-30 years, although differences in approaches and sampling designs among this and previous studies may not allow detection of modest changes. The calculated suspended sediment load reported here is close to the values presented elsewhere, reinforcing the relative importance of this river as a sediment supplier for the Amazon Basin. Seasonality has a significant control on the chemistry of Madeira River waters, and severe decrease in discharge due to anthropogenic changes, such as construction of reservoirs or the occurrence of drier years-a plausible consequence of global climate change-may lead to modification in the chemical composition as well in the sediment deliver to the Amazon River. © 2011 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.","Amazonia; Madeira River; River water chemistry; Rondonia; Suspended sediment","anion; annual variation; anthropogenic effect; bicarbonate; calcium; cation; climate change; concentration (composition); discharge; global change; reservoir; river water; sampling; seasonal variation; sediment transport; suspended sediment; water chemistry; Brazil; Madeira River",,,,,,"(2009) Database, , http://hidroweb.ana.gov.br/, Agência Nacional de Águas-ANA Accessed 1 Mar 2010; Ballester, M.V.R., Victoria, D.C., Krusche, A.V., Coburn, R., Victoria, R.L., Richey, J.E., Logsdon, M.G., Matricardi, E., A remote sensing/GIS-based physical template to understand the biogeochemistry of the Ji-Parana River Basin (Western Amazonia) (2003) Remote Sens Environ, 87 (4), pp. 429-445; Barthem, R., Goulding, M., Forsberg, B., Cañas, C., Ortega, H., (2003) Aquatic Ecology of the Rio Madre De Dios. Scientific Bases for Andes-Amazon Headwaters Conservation, , Lima: Grafica Biblos SA; Bastos, W.R., Gomes, J.P.O., Oliveira, R.C., Almeida, R., Nascimento, E.